context_before: Kiradech Aphibarnrat did not produce the best long game statistics for the tournament but he was very strong in each of the Genworth Short Game Statistics categories.

The 23 year old golfer from Thailand ranked 6th for Scrambles, 5th for Putts per GIR, 6th for Putts per Round and 2nd for 1 Putts per Round, plus he excelled on the Par 3 holes and hit 25% of the Par 5 greens in sub-regulation (two shots).
It has been an incredible two weeks for Kiradech Aphibarnrat, finishing fourth at the Avantha Masters last week before winning here at the Maybank Malaysian Open.
Kiradech APHIBARNRAT -13 Thunderstorms dominated the week right up to the finish of the Maybank Malaysian Open at Kuala Lumpur Golf & Country Club (reducing the tournament to 54 holes).
Kiradech Aphibarnrat emerged as the eventual winner over a host of star studded names.
We analyse his performance together with the other tournament contenders.
context_after: Tournament Stats Result Rank Par 3 Scoring 2.75 2 Par 4 Scoring 3.90 11 Par 5 Scoring 4.42 4 Eagles per Rnd 0.33 2 Birdies per Rnd 5.33 2 Pars per Rnd 10.67 - Bogeys per Rnd 1.67 11 Others per Rnd 0.00 1 Par 5's in 2 3 2 Edoardo MOLINARI -12 Edoardo Molinari fired a bogey free final round of 67 to finish in second place overall (in doing so also making his first cut of the year).

The older of the two Italian golfing brothers hit the ball long and straight off the tee which then enabled him to be very accurate with his approach play (ranking 4th for the Genworth Greens in Regulation statistic).
The winter work with his coach Sean Foley looks to be taking effect.

The Rate of Revolution of various Twining Plants.
If the support be not lofty, the shoot falls to the ground, and resting there, the extremity rises up.
Sometimes several shoots, when flexible, twine together into a cable, and thus support one another.
Single thin depending shoots, such as those of the Sollya Drummondii, will turn abruptly backwards and wind up on themselves.
The greater number of the depending shoots, however, of one twining plant, the Hibbertia dentata, showed but little tendency to turn upwards.

In other cases, as with the Cryptostegia grandiflora, several internodes which were at first flexible and revolved, if they did not succeed in twining round a support, become quite rigid, and supporting themselves upright, carried on their summits the younger revolving internodes.
